1. Neurogenic claudication due to lumbar spinal stenosis (M48.062: Spinal stenosis, lumbar region with neurogenic claudication)
Axial low back pain with radiation down the legs is improving but pain persist. He is currently in physical therapy at NexGen and on gabapentin 300 mg twice daily. He continues to have bilateral EHL weakness and ambulates with a rolling walker. New imaging of the lumbar spine demonstrates Modic type I edematous endplate changes at L4-5 with facet arthropathy and moderate central canal stenosis, there is also severe bilateral foraminal narrowing at L5-S1 with nerve root impingement and a right-sided disc herniation at L2-3.
I have recommended increasing to gabapentin 300 mg 3 times a day, continuing physical therapy and will order a bilateral L5 TFESI under fluoroscopic guidance. He will follow-up with me after the injection.
Any questions the patient had were answered. If the patient's symptoms worsen they were told to call the office or if after hours to proceed to the nearest emergency room or urgent care center.
Any medications distributed were discussed in detail including administration, dosing, and side effects.

text.paragraph:
Back Exercises
The following exercises strengthen the muscles that help to support the trunk (torso) and back. They also help to keep the lower back flexible. Doing these exercises can help to prevent or lessen existing low back pain.
• If you have back pain or discomfort, try doing these exercises 2–3 times each day or as told by your health care provider.
• As your pain improves, do them once each day, but increase the number of times that you repeat the steps for each exercise (do more repetitions).
• To prevent the recurrence of back pain, continue to do these exercises once each day or as told by your health care provider.
Do exercises exactly as told by your health care provider and adjust them as directed. It is normal to feel mild stretching, pulling, tightness, or discomfort as you do these exercises, but you should stop right away if you feel sudden pain or your pain gets worse.
Exercises
Single knee to chest
Repeat these steps 3–5 times for each leg:
1. Lie on your back on a firm bed or the floor with your legs extended.
2. Bring one knee to your chest. Your other leg should stay extended and in contact with the floor.
3. Hold your knee in place by grabbing your knee or thigh with both hands and hold.
4. Pull on your knee until you feel a gentle stretch in your lower back or buttocks.
5. Hold the stretch for 10–30 seconds.
6. Slowly release and straighten your leg.
Pelvic tilt
Repeat these steps 5–10 times:
1. Lie on your back on a firm bed or the floor with your legs extended.
2. Bend your knees so they are pointing toward the ceiling and your feet are flat on the floor.
3. Tighten your lower abdominal muscles to press your lower back against the floor. This motion will tilt your pelvis so your tailbone points up toward the ceiling instead of pointing to your feet or the floor.
4. With gentle tension and even breathing, hold this position for 5–10 seconds.
Cat-cow
Repeat these steps until your lower back becomes more flexible:
1. Get into a hands-and-knees position on a firm bed or the floor. Keep your hands under your shoulders, and keep your knees under your hips. You may place padding under your knees for comfort.
2. Let your head hang down toward your chest. Contract your abdominal muscles and point your tailbone toward the floor so your lower back becomes rounded like the back of a cat.
3. Hold this position for 5 seconds.
4. Slowly lift your head, let your abdominal muscles relax, and point your tailbone up toward the ceiling so your back forms a sagging arch like the back of a cow.
5. Hold this position for 5 seconds.
Press-ups
Repeat these steps 5–10 times:
1. Lie on your abdomen (face-down) on a firm bed or the floor.
2. Place your palms near your head, about shoulder-width apart.
3. Keeping your back as relaxed as possible and keeping your hips on the floor, slowly straighten your arms to raise the top half of your body and lift your shoulders. Do not use your back muscles to raise your upper torso. You may adjust the placement of your hands to make yourself more comfortable.
4. Hold this position for 5 seconds while you keep your back relaxed.
5. Slowly return to lying flat on the floor.
Bridges
Repeat these steps 10 times:
1. Lie on your back on a firm bed or the floor.
2. Bend your knees so they are pointing toward the ceiling and your feet are flat on the floor. Your arms should be flat at your sides, next to your body.
3. Tighten your buttocks muscles and lift your buttocks off the floor until your waist is at almost the same height as your knees. You should feel the muscles working in your buttocks and the back of your thighs. If you do not feel these muscles, slide your feet 1–2 inches (2.5–5 cm) farther away from your buttocks.
4. Hold this position for 3–5 seconds.
5. Slowly lower your hips to the starting position, and allow your buttocks muscles to relax completely.
If this exercise is too easy, try doing it with your arms crossed over your chest.
Abdominal crunches
Repeat these steps 5–10 times:
1. Lie on your back on a firm bed or the floor with your legs extended.
2. Bend your knees so they are pointing toward the ceiling and your feet are flat on the floor.
3. Cross your arms over your chest.
4. Tip your chin slightly toward your chest without bending your neck.
5. Tighten your abdominal muscles and slowly raise your torso high enough to lift your shoulder blades a tiny bit off the floor. Avoid raising your torso higher than that because it can put too much stress on your lower back and does not help to strengthen your abdominal muscles.
6. Slowly return to your starting position.
Back lifts
Repeat these steps 5–10 times:
1. Lie on your abdomen (face-down) with your arms at your sides, and rest your forehead on the floor.
2. Tighten the muscles in your legs and your buttocks.
3. Slowly lift your chest off the floor while you keep your hips pressed to the floor. Keep the back of your head in line with the curve in your back. Your eyes should be looking at the floor.
4. Hold this position for 3–5 seconds.
5. Slowly return to your starting position.
Contact a health care provider if:
• Your back pain or discomfort gets much worse when you do an exercise.
• Your worsening back pain or discomfort does not lessen within 2 hours after you exercise.
If you have any of these problems, stop doing these exercises right away. Do not do them again unless your health care provider says that you can.
Get help right away if:
• You develop sudden, severe back pain. If this happens, stop doing the exercises right away. Do not do them again unless your health care provider says that you can.
This information is not intended to replace advice given to you by your health care provider. Make sure you discuss any questions you have with your health care provider.
